frameDefinitions: A Winner has victory over an Loser.
This frame contains adjectives and nouns that describe the truth or sincerity of communication.
In this frame a Theme is moved by a Vehicle which is not directly under their power.
The Outcome of a contest is described in terms of the Margin between what would be required for victory and the actual Outcome.
A Dodger acts to avoid an oncoming moving Bad_entity.
In this frame a Profiled_item is higher that its Standard_item on a scale with respect to some Attribute.
frameExamples: Evelyn was <t>candid</t> with me about the party.
The Basque nationalists won a <t>narrow</t> victory in the regional elections on Sunday.
Mo <t>dodged</t>  the flower pot that Larry threw in disgust.
Notices for the Shield Theater's production of Macbeth <t>surpassed</t> all previous reviews .
listRoleDefinitions: The individual or individuals who beat the <fen>Loser</fen>.
The individual or individuals that get beat by the <fen>Winner</fen>.
When the <fen>Winner</fen> has victory over the <fen>Loser</fen>.
The location where the <fen>Winner</fen> has victory <fen>Loser</fen>.

The <fen>Speaker</fen> produces the <fen>Message</fen>, the truth or sincerity of which is at issue. It is normally expressed as the External Argument of predicative uses of the <t>target</t> word, or as the Nominal Head of prenominal uses.

<fen>Message</fen> is the communicative content whose truth or sincerity is at issue. This role does not normally co-occur with the other FEs in this frame. When it does occur, it is normally the External Argument of a predicative use of the <t>Target</t> word, or the modified Nominal Head in a prenominal use.

The <fen>Topic</fen> is the subject matter to which the <fen>Message</fen> pertains. It often occurs without the <fen>Message</fen> role in predicative uses of the <t>target</t> word. It is normally expressed as a PP Complement headed by 'about'.
<fen>Medium</fen> is the physical or abstract setting in which the <fen>Message</fen> is conveyed.
The <fen>Theme</fen> is the entity which moves by means of the <fen>Vehicle</fen>.
The <fen>Vehicle</fen> is the means of conveyance of the <fen>Theme</fen>. It is usually expressed in a <ment>PP</ment>-complement or the direct object.
Any expression which implies a definite starting-point of motion expresses the frame element <fen>Source</fen>.
The <fen>Path</fen> describes the trajectory of the motion.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is the endpoint of the trajectory of motion.
The Area is the location where the motion takes place.
When the riding takes place.
The <fen>Outcome</fen> of a contest whose <fen>Margin</fen> is under consideration.
The difference between the minimum required for victory and the actual <fen>Outcome</fen>.
A modifier expressing  the deviation of the <fen>Value</fen> from what is expected given the <fen>Outcome</fen> and the <fen>Value</fen> indicated by the target.
The generally implicit <fen>Value</fen> of the <fen>Margin</fen>.
The <fen>Dodger</fen> acts to avoid an oncoming <fen>Bad_entity</fen>.
The <fen>Bad_entity</fen> is  the oncoming entity to avoid.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> at which the dodging occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the dodging occurs.
The role <fen>Standard_item</fen> denotes the entities that are exceeded by the <fen>Item</fen> with regard to the <fen>Attribute</fen>.
The <fen>Profiled_item</fen> is the entity that is located closest to the end of the scale evoked by some <fen>Attribute</fen>.
The <fen>Attribute</fen> is a property that evokes a scale along which the <fen>Item</fen> is located closer to one extreme in  comparison to the <fen>Standard_item</fen>.
The <fen>Standard_attribute</fen> is used when the standard is a specific value on  a scale.
The <fen>Profiled_attribute</fen> is a particular value on a scale which is being compared to an <fen>Attribute</fen> or <fen>Standard_item</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Item</fen> is higher on the scale than the <fen>Standard</fen>.
listRoleExamples: Evelyn made some candid remarks <fex>in French</fex>.
Professor Frink sailed to Italy <fex>on an oceanliner</fex>.
We will fly back to New York <fex>in September</fex>.
<fex>Mo</fex> dodged the flower pot that Larry threw in disgust.
Mo dodged <fex> the flower pot that Larry threw in disgust</fex>.
In her time, she outstripped <fex>most politician in the country</fex>.
<fex>The buildings</fex> were outstripped in beauty and grace many years ago.
